# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .env.example - Environment Variable Configuration Template
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# What is this file?
#
# This file serves as a template and a comprehensive list of all the environment
# variables that the application requires to run correctly. It provides a clear
# structure for developers to see what configuration options are available and
# necessary.
#
# IMPORTANT: This file should NOT contain any sensitive information or secrets
# like API keys, database passwords, or private keys. It is meant to be a
# *safe-to-commit* example that is shared across the development team.
#
#
# How is it related to the .env file?
#
# The actual configuration is loaded from a file named `.env`, which is NOT
# committed to version control (it should be listed in your .gitignore file).
# The `.env` file is specific to each environment (local, staging, production)
# and contains the actual secrets and configuration values.
#
#
# How to use this file:
#
# To set up your local environment, you should:
# 1. Create a copy of this file and name it `.env`.
#    In your terminal, you can run: cp .env.example .env
#
# 2. Open the newly created `.env` file and fill in the appropriate values
#    for your specific environment. For example, update the database
#    credentials with your local database information.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- LLM Settings ---
OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://***.openai.azure.com/openai/v1/
OPENAI_API_KEY=***
MODEL_NAME=gpt-4.1
